南极冰盖的熔融率主要受到南极周围的海洋温度的增加来控制。利用新的高分辨率气候模型模拟，来自乌得勒支大学的科学家发现与具有较粗分辨率的电流模拟相比，越来越慢的海洋温度升高。因此，100岁的预计海平面上升约为目前模拟预期的25％。这些结果今天发表于“社科”科学进展。未来海平面上升的估计是基于气候模拟的大集合。这些模拟的产出有助于了解未来的气候变化及其对海平面的影响。气候研究人员不断旨在改进这些模型，例如，通过使用更高的空间分辨率，以考虑更多细节。 ＆＃34;高分辨率模拟可以更准确地确定更准确，＆＃34; Henk Dijkstra教授说。和他的博士一起。候选人RenéVanWesten，他在过去几年中一直在高分辨率气候模型模拟中学习。
    新的高分辨率模型考虑了海洋涡流。涡流是一个大（10-200公里）的海洋循环中的旋转和湍流，有助于运输热量和盐。将海洋漩涡添加到导致南极围绕南极洲的海洋温度的更现实的代表性，这是确定南极冰盖的质量损失的关键。 ＆＃34;南极冰盖被冰架包围，减少了陆地冰流入海洋，＆＃34; van westen解释道。 ＆＃34;南极洲周围的高海温度会增加这些冰架的融化，导致陆地冰加入海洋，从而导致更多的海平面上升。＆＃34;
   目前的气候模型模拟，不考虑海洋漩涡，南极洲周围的海洋温度在气候变化下正在增加。新的高分辨率模拟显示了相当不同的行为和南极洲附近的一些地区，甚至在气候变化下很酷。 ＆＃34;这些区域似乎在气候变化下更具弹性，＆＃34; van Westen说。 Dijkstra补充说：＆＃34;一个人因海洋涡流效应而获得了一个非常不同的反应。＆＃34;
    由于冰货架熔体，新的高分辨率模型突出了较小的质量损失：与当前的气候模型相比仅三分之一。 Van Westen提到，这将在即将到来的100年内减少预计的全球海平面上涨25％。 ＆＃34;虽然海平面将继续上升，但这是低洼地区的好消息。在我们的模拟中，海洋漩涡在海平面投影中发挥着至关重要的作用，表明这些小规模的功能可以具有全球效果。＆＃34;
  这支球队大约一年才能在阿姆斯特丹的Surfsara国家超级计算机上完成高分辨率模型模拟。 Dijkstra：＆＃34;这些高分辨率模型需要巨大的计算量，但是揭示了较小的物理过程，揭示了在研究变革时应考虑的较小尺寸的物理流程。＆＃34;更多信息：r.m. van westen el al。海洋漩涡强烈影响全球平均海平面预测。科学推进（2021年）。 riponance.sciencemag.org/lookup ... .1126 / sciadv.abf1674

note_en:
The melting rate of the Antarctic ice sheet is mainly controlled by the increase of ocean temperatures surrounding Antarctica. Using a new, higher-resolution climate model simulation, scientists from Utrecht University found a much slower ocean temperature increase compared to current simulations with a coarser resolution. Consequently, the projected sea-level rise in 100 years is about 25% lower than expected from the current simulations. These results are published today in the journal  Science Advances.    Estimates for future sea-level rise are based on a large ensemble of climate   simulations. The output from these simulations helps to understand future climate change and its effects on the sea level. Climate researchers continually aim to improve these models, for example by using a much higher spatial resolution that takes more details into account. &#34;High-resolution simulations can determine the   much more accurately,&#34; says Prof. Henk Dijkstra. Together with his Ph.D. candidate René van Westen, he has been studying   in high-resolution climate model simulations over the past few years.
    The new high-resolution model takes into account ocean eddy processes. An eddy is a large (10-200 km) swirling and turbulent feature in the ocean circulation, which contributes to the transport of heat and salt. Adding ocean eddies into the   leads to a more realistic representation of the ocean temperatures surrounding Antarctica, which is key for determining the mass loss of the Antarctic ice sheet. &#34;The Antarctic ice sheet is surrounded by ice shelves which reduce the flow of land ice into the ocean,&#34; Van Westen explains. &#34;Higher ocean temperatures around Antarctica increase the melting of these ice shelves, resulting in an acceleration of land ice into the ocean and consequently leading to more sea-level rise.&#34;
   The current climate model simulations, which do not take ocean eddies into account, project that the ocean temperatures around Antarctica are increasing under climate change. The new high-resolution simulation shows quite different behavior and some regions near Antarctica even cool under climate change. &#34;These regions appear to be more resilient under climate change,&#34; says Van Westen. Dijkstra adds: &#34;One obtains a very different   response due to ocean-eddy effects.&#34;
    The new high-resolution model projects a smaller mass loss as a result of ice-shelf melt: only one third compared to current climate models. This reduces the projected global sea-level rise by 25% in the upcoming 100 years, Van Westen mentions. &#34;Although sea levels will continue to rise, this is good news for low-lying regions. In our simulation, ocean eddies play a crucial role in sea-level projections, showing that these small-scale   features can have a global effect.&#34;
  It took the team about one year to complete the high-resolution model simulation on the national supercomputer at SURFsara in Amsterdam. Dijkstra: &#34;These high-resolution models require an immense amount of computation, but are valuable as they reveal smaller-scale physical processes which should be taken into account when studying   change.&#34;        More information:												R.M. van Westen el al. Ocean eddies strongly affect global mean sea-level projections.  Science Advances (2021).  advances.sciencemag.org/lookup … .1126/sciadv.abf1674
